Title: RAY
Credit: written by
Author: brehon
Draft date: 2026-06-02
Source: a brehon story

FADE IN:

INT. DELANEY'S TAVERN - NIGHT

Smoke. A low jukebox. A back booth that every chair in the place is angled a few degrees toward.

RAY -- thirties, slight, sharp-eyed -- nurses a flat half-beer like a man holding court. Across from him a BIG MAN in a feed cap, red in the face, mid-sermon.

BIG MAN
-- somebody's got to stand up for this country. That's all I'm saying.

Ray sets the beer down. Unhurried.

RAY
Name the rubber company.

BIG MAN
The -- what?

RAY
The one that owns the plantations your boy's defending. You can't. But the man who signed the shipping contract can. And he won't be in any rice paddy. Neither will his sons.

A beat.

RAY
Yours will.

The Big Man's mouth opens. Nothing comes out of it.

RAY
That's not standing up for your country. That's standing up for a man you'll never meet, who'd step over your kid's body to make his train.

Ray picks the beer back up.

RAY
But you go ahead. Be proud.

Laughter rolls down the bar. A hand slides Ray a fresh beer. The Big Man stares into his.

Ray takes the tribute with a small nod. The king, at rest.

And UNDER THE TABLE, where the room can't see it --

-- Ray's right hand is a white-knuckled fist, the whole arm trembling, taut as a strung wire. A body with a fight in it and nowhere on earth to put it.

He catches it himself. Presses the hand flat to his thigh. Stills it.

CUT TO:

EXT. CREEK - DAY (FLASHBACK)

A hand-lettered card over the water: TWENTY YEARS EARLIER.

TOMMY, nine years old, drags himself up the muddy bank. Split lip, one eye swelling shut. Behind him a BIGGER BOY, eleven, stands with his fists still up and his chest heaving -- somehow the more frightened of the two.

Tommy spits red into the dirt.

And grins.

He turns around. Walks back down the bank, toward the bigger boy, to take some more.

EXT. FARMHOUSE PORCH - CONTINUOUS

Forty yards off, on the porch rail, YOUNG RAY -- fourteen, a book open on his knee -- watches. Perfectly still. Doing the arithmetic.

He does not get up.

He watches his little brother walk back into a beating he cannot win, and something crosses his face that is not fear -- something he files away and does not name.

He turns a page.

CUT TO:

INT. FARMHOUSE KITCHEN - MORNING (PRESENT)

A folded sheet of Army paper, squared dead-center on the oilcloth. TOMMY -- nineteen now, big, plain, open-faced -- smooths it flat under his thumb. Again. Again.

Ray comes in pulling on his undershirt. Stops. Reads the table.

TOMMY
Went down to the courthouse.

A long beat. Then Ray sits, and the machine starts up.

RAY
You're a body to them, Tommy. A line item.

He yanks a folded newspaper from a drawer, slaps it down -- columns of the dead.

RAY
By province. I can show you the math. You come home in a bag or you don't come home, and it changes nothing, because this war was a lie before either one of us was born.

Tommy turns his coffee cup. A slow quarter-circle. Says nothing.

Ray keeps going. We lose the sound of it -- we only watch: the best argument of the man's life, every word of it landing on a boy as movable as a fence post.

Ray runs dry.

Tommy nods. Like he's been agreeing the whole time.

TOMMY
I know all that, Ray.

He stands. Goes to pack.

Ray sits alone with his tables full of dead men. The one argument he has ever lost.

INT. FARMHOUSE KITCHEN - AT THE WINDOW - LATER

Ray at the glass.

Through it: Tommy crosses the gray yard, duffel on his shoulder, the paper in his breast pocket, walking away down the long dirt road.

Ray's hand rises. Presses flat against the cold glass.

He does not rap it. Does not call out.

In the window his own reflection floats over his brother's shrinking back. His chest lifts -- and holds. A breath he won't let go.

His lips part. Nothing comes. The man of words, with none of them.

Tommy thins to a smudge. Then nothing.

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. COUNTRY CHURCH - DAY

A flag-draped box on a caisson. A bugler. Low clouds.

INT. CHURCH - CONTINUOUS

Rows of wet faces. One dry one: RAY. Bolt-still, a current running somewhere under the stone.

The line files past with their soft hands. He takes each, releases each, gives back nothing.

MRS. ELLIS -- seventies, Tommy's old Sunday-school teacher -- takes his hand and holds on.

MRS. ELLIS
The Lord never sends us more than we can carry, Raymond.

Ray looks at her. Holds the look until she lets go.

RAY
He didn't send it. A man in an office did.

(beat)
I can get you the name.

He walks out -- leaving her with her mouth open, the way he's left a hundred men at the bar.

But there's no jury here. Nobody laughs. And his face, going through the door, says it gave him nothing at all.

CUT TO:

INT. RAY'S HOUSE - NIGHT

One bulb. Ray at the kitchen table. In front of him: his father's revolver, a box of shells.

He loads it. Calm. Methodical. The hands sure.

On the wall behind him, a photograph -- two boys at a creek, squinting into the sun.

He stands. Pockets the gun. Takes his coat off the hook.

EXT. RECRUITING OFFICE - DAY

A storefront. A flag in the window. A faded poster: a square-jawed soldier pointing out at the street.

Ray's car eases to the curb. He sits a moment. Then he crosses to the door.

INT. RECRUITING OFFICE - CONTINUOUS

A RECRUITER -- late twenties, tired, buried in paperwork -- glances up halfway, doesn't really see him.

Ray stops just inside the door. Hand in his coat, around the grip.

And in the dark glass of the door he catches himself: a man, squared up, a hand on a gun.

Insert -- Ray's hand inside the coat: dead steady on the revolver. Not a tremor.

Flash -- the white-knuckled fist shaking under the tavern table.

Back to the hand now. Still as stone.

Something moves behind Ray's eyes. Not a decision. A recognition.

RECRUITER
Help you?

Ray's hand comes out of the coat. Empty.

RAY
I want to sign up.

The recruiter slides a clipboard across the desk. Ray picks up the pen.

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. FIREBASE - TREELINE - DAY (WAR)

Hell. Mortars walking the treeline, fountains of red dirt, men screaming. A SOLDIER an arm's length from Ray is simply -- gone. A smear, a ringing.

Ray stands up in it. And waits.

Close on his face -- waiting for the cold hands. The freeze. The porch.

It doesn't come.

The roar drops away to almost nothing. The inside of a held breath.

And Ray is already moving -- low, fast, calm and unhurried at once, ahead of any thought. He seizes a pinned, screaming kid -- ECHOLS, eighteen -- by the webbing, hauls him out of the open, his other hand putting rounds back down the line. Economical. Sure. A man who has finally found the one tool his hands were built for.

He drags Echols behind a berm. Holds the corner. Fires. Reloads. Fires.

EXT. FIREBASE - BERM - LATER

Quiet. Smoke drifting sideways. Echols -- alive -- has fistfuls of Ray's sleeve, sobbing, saying thank you, thank you, thank you.

Ray doesn't hear a word of it.

He's somewhere else. A strange calm on his face, head tipped a little, like a man listening to something far off that he knows.

RAY (V.O.)
(barely a breath)
There you are.

CUT TO:

INT. DELANEY'S TAVERN - NIGHT (TWO YEARS LATER)

Same smoke. Same jukebox. Same booth.

A NEW KID -- twenties, sharp, nursing one beer -- holds the floor, mid-flight.

NEW KID
-- a rich man's war and a poor man's funeral. Nobody in this room can even name the rubber company.

The regulars grin. A couple of them cut a glance toward the door --

-- where RAY sits on a stool. Older. Quieter. Weather in his face. Some of them remember whose lines those are.

The Kid catches the glances, follows them to Ray, lights up -- friendly, hungry, exactly the way Ray used to.

NEW KID
You were over there, weren't you? Go on. Tell me I'm wrong.

The whole room leans in. The throne, held open for him.

Ray looks at the Kid a long moment. The fast mouth. The captive jury. The safe little war you win every single night without once standing up.

Nothing pulls.

He drains his beer. Sets a coin on the bar. Stands.

He crosses to the Kid -- the room holding its breath for the old Ray, for the dismantling --

-- and stops at his shoulder.

RAY
You're not wrong.

(beat)
Doesn't matter. Go anyway.

Ray walks out into the daylight.

The door swings shut on the Kid -- mouth open, beer going warm -- trying to work out whether he just won.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
